‘The sea is ours’: Bolivia’s landlocked country hopes the court will reopen access to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors patrol around the sailing-decorated naval command in La Paz.
There are ocean blue flags on public buildings.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, naval bases proclaim the motto: “We have the right to the sea.
It's our duty to get it back."
In the coastal Bolivia, the memories of the lost beach, which Chile took in a bloody conflict for resources in the 19th century, are still vivid, and there is a strong desire to rewind the waves of the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps the strongest in decades, as Bolivia is awaiting the final judgment of the International Court of Justice on October 1st, five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has the ball, which gives a spirit of belonging and peace to people who are looking forward to a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
A lot of Bolivians are watching the decision of the International Court of Justice on projectors, hoping that the Hague Court will stand up for Bolivia, and after decades of rapsodical attitude, Chile will be obliged to sit at the negotiating table so Bolivia can have independent access to the sea.
Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, Evo Morales, who faces a controversial battle for re-election next year, has much to lose with Monday’s verdict.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he said in late August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favour of Bolivia, and that it would not change the situation much if it were to be favourable to Bolivia.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no power to judge Chilean territories and has also stipulated that it will not affect the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the judgment of the International Court of Justice was delivered less than six months after the closing arguments indicates that the case was “not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, an expert in international law in Chile.
