“The issue of the sea exit has been diverted by the current Bolivian government for its own purposes”, Mr. Zárate explained.
“Because of Morales’s hostile rhetoric, the Chileans’ remaining goodwill has gone away.”
Bolivia and Chile will certainly continue to negotiate at some point, but after what has happened, it will be extremely difficult to initiate a dialogue.
The two countries have not delegated an ambassador since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, disagrees with the finding that judicial decision-making was unusually fast.
Monday is an “exceptional opportunity to open a new chapter in relations with Chile” and a chance for “both of them to come out of 139 years of conflict,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, would have used the maritime debate to turn it into a political advantage.
