John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
The Scottish independent schools have traditionally provided excellent education. In view of the recent outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed to 2018, which is only further strengthened by the individual and group success in sports, art, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30,000 students are already studying in institutions of this kind, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which strive to provide students and parents with the best possible services.
Independent schools seek to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers, and what positions they hold as citizens of the world.
In an education sector where it is possible to design and implement tailor-made school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to prove to be popular and sought-after subjects.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language they understand, it goes to their head.
But if you speak his language, it goes to his heart."
This is an important reminder, because we cannot rely solely on English to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year's exam results show that students from independent schools across the country have achieved the best results from foreign languages.
68 percent of all students who studied a foreign language achieved a higher A degree (more than 85 percent).
According to data collected from the 74 member schools of SCIS, 72 percent of students received a higher grade of A from Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students reached grade A.
These results also confirm that independent schools in Scotland view foreign languages as essential knowledge, which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages have become as important as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics, both in independent and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Vocational Training found that 17% of employers said they found it difficult to fill vacancies due to a lack of language skills.
This shows that language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for young people to have a successful career.
As more and more workplaces expect knowledge of foreign languages, language skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career path a person chooses, if he has studied a foreign language, he will gain a lifetime of persistent knowledge from which he will have a clear advantage.
Being able to communicate directly with other nationalities automatically gives a multi-lingual candidate a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents could not speak a foreign language well enough to communicate with others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10 percent (15 percent).
It is therefore important to focus on the teaching of languages to children.
Speaking several languages, especially in developing countries, can be a tool in the hands of children that gives them a better chance of applying for important jobs as adults.
In Scotland, different languages will be used in each school.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while many will teach languages such as Mandarin or Japanese that are expected to be of paramount importance to the UK by 2020.
Whatever your child’s area of interest, you will learn several optional languages at independent schools and will be trained by tutors who are experts in their field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment for children that equips and equips them with the skills they will need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It is not difficult to see that in the current global business environment, languages remain vital for the future of a country, and education must reflect this.
In fact, knowledge of modern languages should rather be treated as "international communication skills".
Independent schools offer choice, diversity and quality education to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire – that's how it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
