There is no way that North Korea will unilaterally disarm if it does not trust its negotiating partner.
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that maintaining sanctions has only increased mistrust of the United States, and there is no way that under these circumstances the country would unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Jongho said at the annual UN General Assembly that North Korea took "significant and generous steps" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, shutting down nuclear testing sites and promising not to expand its nuclear arsenal and the scope of nuclear technology.
“Unfortunately, we don’t see any similar response from the Americans,” he said.
“In the absence of confidence in America, we feel that the security of our nation is not guaranteed, and under these circumstances there is no way that we can unilaterally and firstly disarm.”
Although Ri reiterated North Korea's disappointment that Washington was resisting the idea of "staged" nuclear disarmament, which would receive North Korea's rewards for the steps taken so far, his statement seemed significant because he did not clearly reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done so far.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a US president in power and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, during which Kim promised to work on “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula” while Trump guaranteed the integrity of North Korea.
North Korea is trying to make it official at the end of the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States believes that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
The United States has also not been subject to tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“America insists that we start with nuclear disarmament and increases the pressure with sanctions to impose its will on us, and it also protests against the possibility of declaring the end of the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that we can be brought to our knees by sanctions is a dream of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that non-relief sanctions only increase our suspicions."
Ri did not mention that a second summit between Kim and Trump was planned, but the US President specifically mentioned it at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister stressed that three meetings had taken place between Kim and the South Korean President, Mun Jein, in the last five months, and then added: “If the country involved in nuclear disarmament were South Korea, not the United States of America, then the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have been in such a stalemate.”
Nevertheless, Ri's speech differed dramatically from last year's when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the North American continent with North Korean missiles was inevitable after Trump, "the evil president", called Kim "the rocket man", who was on a suicide mission.
This year, at the UN, Trump, who threatened North Korea with “total destruction” last year, praised Kim for having the courage to take steps towards disarmament, but also noted that there is still much work to do and sanctions will remain until North Korea implements nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said that there was no time limit, i.e. “If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council could reward Pyongyang for the actions taken so far.
On the other hand, the US Secretary of State, Mike Pompeo, said in the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The sanctions of the Security Council must be adhered to unwaveringly until we have achieved actual, final, demonstrable nuclear disarmament.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously maintained sanctions against North Korea in order to reduce the financing of Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri during the break of the UN General Assembly and then said that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has been to North Korea three times this year, but his last trip didn't go well.
After leaving Pyongyang in July, he announced that progress had been made, but North Korea accused him hours later of making "gangster-like demands".
During the meeting with Mun this month, North Korea promised to dismantle a missile base and a nuclear facility if the United States took "the necessary steps."
According to Mun, the "right steps" mentioned by Kim would be security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore and actions that could lead to the normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students are taught to get enough rest.
A new subject at Harvard University this year encouraged students to sleep more, fighting against the increasingly popular macho culture of caffeine-fueled all-night learning.
One academic concluded that students at the world’s number one university are often completely lost when it comes to how they should care for themselves.
The course, which he believes is the first such training in the USA, was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and practices as a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
He encouraged the development of the course by giving a lecture earlier on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I just facing this now as a senior?’
He said that no one ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told the Telegraph.
During the course, which was first launched this year, students will be introduced to the fundamental impact of proper sleep habits on their academic and sports performance, in addition to having a positive impact on their general well-being.
According to Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical College and director of the university's health service, the university decided to start the course because during the week the students were found to be extremely sleepless.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one, for example, they show a picture of a dorm room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and why bedtime routines are important.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
They present a map of the university area with interactive icons to encourage participants to rethink their daily routine.
“We know we’re not going to change student behavior right away.
But we believe they have a right to this knowledge, just as they have a right to be aware of the health effects of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
A culture in which it is considered an achievement to study a night continues to flourish, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students result in increasing problems of sleeplessness.
Sufficient and quality sleep protects students from stress, exhaustion and anxiety, even from obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain to starve and causes a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler design the course, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and biophysics, and last year he took one of the professor's courses as a freshman at Harvard.
He said that what he heard there opened his eyes and encouraged him to defend the launch of a university-level training.
He hopes that, as a next step, postgraduate students will be able to participate in a similar training programme before entering the private sector.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set a warning for going to bed, a wake-up call for waking up, and familiarize themselves with the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electric screens and LED light sources, which can easily dissuade them from the daily rhythm and make it difficult to fall asleep.
