An excerpt from our "Sunday breakfast" almanach: September 30, 1882, now exactly 136 years ago... the day the later physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that could have led to the creation of a device known as the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter has been one of the basic tools of science ever since, and thanks to the film "Bells of Coronado" (Coronado bells) featuring strange cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans in 1950, it has become part of pop culture:
Man: "What is this?"
Rogers: “This is a Geiger counter. It can be used to look for radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
If you put on these headphones, you can hear the sound of atoms being emitted because of the radioactivity of minerals."
Evans: "Listen, it's bouncing."
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
However, he lives on in his invention bearing his name.
New vaccine against cancer may teach immune system to ‘see’ abnormal cells
New Vaccine Against Cancer May Teach Immune System to ‘See’ and Destroy Abnormal Cells
A vaccine given as part of a treatment teaches the immune system to recognise abnormal cells.
Part of the method is to extract immune cells from the patient and then modify them in a lab.
Thus, they are able to “see” the protein that accompanies many types of cancer.
An experimental vaccine has produced promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who was treated with a vaccine that taught the immune system to recognize abnormal cells could say goodbye to ovarian cancer for more than 18 months.
Part of the method is the extraction of immune cells from the patient; their modification in the laboratory to “see” a protein called HER2, which is a common accompaniment of several cancers; and then the replanting of cells.
Jay Berzofsky, professor of the American National Cancer Institute (Bethesda, Maryland), said: “Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 “stimulates the growth of several types of cancer,” including breast, ovarian, lung and rectal cancer, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar method, based on highlighting immune cells and “teaching” them how to attack cancer cells, has already been successfully used in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
