HIV/AIDS: 14% increase in new patients in China
China announced that the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS in the country has increased by 14%.
According to health officials, this means more than 820,000 people affected.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, the number of reported cases increased by about 40,000.
Compared to the previous ones, it is a change that the vast majority of newly infected people catch the disease sexually.
The disease had previously spread rapidly by transfusing infected blood in parts of China.
However, health officials at a conference in Yunnan Province said that the number of such cases has since fallen to nearly zero.
Despite this, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 compared to the previous year.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem for the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has not been a crime in China since 1997, but discrimination against the community has been very strong ever since.
According to estimates in various studies, 70-70% of men who have sex with other men end up marrying women because of the conservative values of the country.
In many cases, the disease spreads because of inadequate sexual protection.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided universal access to anti-HIV drugs as part of a program to solve the problem.
