Johnny English strikes again, or Rowan Atkinson's lame spy comedy
Today it has become a tradition to look for references to Brexit in all British-related films, and there can be no exception to this franchise under the name Johnny English, which can be classified as an action comedy/parody, the first part of which, Johnny English in 2003, the second part of Johnny English was reloaded in 2011.
Will the British nation become a new export product of sarcastic, self-parodic satyrs, in which we make fun of our own obvious lameness?
What is certain is that Johnny English had enough ammunition for another return – it is clear from his name that this comic character was created so that the crowds of viewers in the cinemas of non-English-speaking countries of the world could laugh at him.
Johnny English is, of course, a loony secret agent who thinks he's charming with his bizarre manners, so he reminds me a little of Inspector Clouseau, sometimes Mr. Bean, and occasionally the guy who contributed to the theme song of the Fire Wheels at the opening ceremony of the 2012 London Olympics.
The character was originally based on the mysterious international traveler Atkinson once played in a long-forgotten Barclaycard TV commercial and left chaos everywhere.
There are a few good moments in the last Johnny English movie.
I loved how Johnny English, dressed in medieval armor, approached a helicopter, and when he got there, the rotors knocked on his helmet for a few moments.
Atkinson's comic vein prevails in the film, but the humor of the film does not really work, and it even seems unnecessary, since nowadays "serious" franchises such as James Bond films or Mission Impossible series also bravely touch the tool of humor.
It feels like the humor of the film is more aimed at children, and for me, Johnny English's crazy, failed adventures do not reach the level of ingenuity and genius that Atkinson brings to the silent scenes of the Mr. Bean series.
The starting point of the film is eternal: Britain is in grave danger.
A cybercriminal broke into the British spy network's top-secret online network and revealed the identity of all British agents to the horror of the on-duty agent Kevin Eldon, who, unfortunately, only got such a small role in the film.
This could be the final nail in the coffin of the conceited and divisive prime minister, whose political popularity is already in ruins: Emma Thompson is practically playing Theresa May and making everything out of the otherwise poorly written character.
His intelligence advisors will outline to him that since the identity of all active agents has been revealed, he will have to put a retired agent on the job.
This retired agent, of course, is the clumsy Johnny English, who has been working as a teacher at a prestigious school since his retirement, but, by way of derogation from the curriculum, teaches children to spy – of course, there are funny scenes here, while English describes the basics of espionage in a "Rocksuli" way.
English is quickly transported to Whitehall, where at the emergency briefing he meets his former long-suffering armor carrier, Bough, who is still being played by Ben Miller.
Bough has been married ever since, and he has married the captain of a submarine who always talks to his ears – the captain is played by Vicki Pepperdine, who is destined for much better roles.
So the two-handed "Batman and Robin" pair of His Majesty's National Security Service will take action again and confront Ophelia Bulletova, played by the beautiful Olga Kurylenko, as a real woman of destiny.
Meanwhile, the Prime Minister is increasingly ensnared by the charismatic IT billionaire who claims to be able to solve Britain's digital problems: his name is Jason Volta, and Jake Lacy plays him.
English and Bough begin their clown mission: disguised as waiters, they set fire to a fancy French restaurant, then smuggle themselves into Volta's luxury yacht in the midst of an amazing commotion, and English really releases hell when he tries to get to know Volta's apartment using a VR-headset.
We need these stations to get to the end, but as cheerful and twisted as it is, it may give the impression of a children's film a little too much.
The end result is pretty mediocre.
As with all the other Johnny English films, the question is, can't the British film industry finally give Rowan Atkinson a role worthy of his talent?
