What is the Global Citizen Festival and have you managed to reduce poverty?
The annual Global Citizen Festival begins in New York on Saturday. The festival features world stars to stand up for a truly noble goal: the global eradication of poverty.
The Global Citizen Festival is now being held for the seventh time, with tens of thousands expected to fill Central Park's Great Lawn, where participants can not only enjoy Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes, but also draw attention to the real purpose of the event: to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival was first held in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty Project. The project is run by an international advocacy group aimed at eradicating poverty by involving more and more people in the active fight against poverty.
Free tickets to the concert (unless they are willing to pay for VIP tickets) can be given to those who undertake certain tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, e-mailing a leading politician, a phone call or any other meaningful activity to draw attention to the aim of the project: the eradication of poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen really been over the last 12 years in achieving its goals?
Is it really an effective tool to reward people with concert tickets in order to convince others of the importance of action, or is it just another form of so-called "clicktivism" when people feel that they have made a meaningful contribution to a case by signing or writing an online petition on Twitter?
Since 2011, according to Global Citizen data, more than 19 million "actions" have been carried out by project supporters, which have served a number of different purposes.
According to the organization, these actions have helped world leaders allocate $37 billion to anti-poverty policies and commitments that could impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group claimed 390 commitments and announcements that they were derived from their actions, of which $10 billion had already been paid or collected during fundraising.
The group estimates that the money raised has already directly affected the lives of nearly 649 million people.
The main commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership between investors and contractors aimed at "helping children reach their potential". The organization promised Rwanda $35 million to help eradicate hunger after receiving more than 4700 Twitter messages from "global citizens".
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can banish social injustice and malnutrition as footnotes in the history books,” Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition, told the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also claims that after asking the UK to improve the nutrition of mothers and their children in more than 5,000 actions, the government has earmarked funds for the Power of Nutrition project, which will improve the nutrition of 5 million women and children.
One of the frequently asked questions posted on the Global Citizen website is “Why do you think extreme poverty can be eliminated?”.
According to the Global Citizen: “It will be a long and difficult journey, where we sometimes get stuck and sometimes fail.
But like the previous civil rights and anti-segregation movements, we will achieve our goal because together we are stronger."
Janet Jackson, Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe will perform at this year's New York event, and the hosts will be Deborah-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
