The inventor of the World Wide Web would launch a new Internet to confront Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee's open source platform Solid.
With Solid, users can choose where they want to store their data and who can access each information.
In his exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was "to gain control of the world".
“We have to do it now,” he said of the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own "personal online data warehouse", also known as POD.
It can include lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available from the same browser at the same time.
The unique thing about the personal online data repository is that the user can fully decide who can access his data.
The company calls this "implementation of the right of individuals to self-determination over data".
According to John Bruce, CEO of Inrupt, the company's task is to provide resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contracted developers working in the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
From this week on, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt.
According to Berners-Lee, he and his team do not ask "Facebook and Google to introduce the whole change-making technology that would turn the business models of companies completely upside down overnight."
“We don’t ask permission from them.”
Berners-Lee said: “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that will help protect the integrity and quality of the new Solid grid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the University of Technology in Massachusetts.
Berners-Lee has been an important opinion-maker in recent months in the debates surrounding the neutrality of the Internet.
Despite the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I am extremely optimistic about the next era of the World Wide Web,” Berners-Lee said.
