The National Trust investigates the secret life of bats
New research is being conducted on a Scottish-Highland estate to find out how bats exploit the characteristics of the landscape during hunting.
Researchers hope the results will provide new information on the behaviour of unique flying mammals, which could benefit future species conservation initiatives.
Scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will investigate the behavior of common and soprano dwarf bats, as well as brown long-eared bats and water bats in the Inverewe Garden area in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at appropriate points in the area to record bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will use hand-held detectors to collect mobile data.
Detailed analysis of the recordings can determine the frequency of bat sounds and what species are doing.
Researchers also prepare a habitat map and report to determine in detail how the behaviour of animals depends on the landscape.
Rob Dewar, the NTS conservation advisor, hopes the results will reveal which habitats are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the beneficial effects of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, and how best to preserve forested areas for bats and other affected species.
The size of bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom has decreased significantly over the last century.
Construction and land development work disrupt the animals’ sleeping areas and reduce their living space.
Wind turbines and street lighting are also a risk factor for them, as are flypapers posted, certain chemical processes used for building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't actually completely blind.
However, because of their nocturnal predatory nature, they rely more on their hearing when hunting prey than on their sight.
With their sophisticated technique based on ultrasound reflection, they can determine the exact position of insects and landmarks in their path.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
They work with ten trained professionals who regularly conduct studies and sleep site tests and are sometimes involved in rescue work.
The organization established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat trees.
According to estate manager David Thompson, the area is an ideal habitat for bats.
“There’s a great place for bats here in Threeve,” he said.
“There are old buildings, lots of old trees, and everything else you need for a good living space.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats, and thanks to the work we’ve done here and in other areas, we can learn more about what it takes to make them feel great.”
He also highlighted the importance of making sure that bats live there before the renovation of buildings, as the destruction of a single colony could result in the destruction of 400 females and young individuals, which could lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected animals, their destruction, harassment and disturbance of their habitat are prohibited by law.
Elisabeth Ferrell, representative of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, also asked for the help of the population.
He said: “There is still much we do not know about bats, and we have almost no information about the situation of the population of most domestic species.”
