Central Celebs is mainly characterised by fishing and farming, especially in the coastal areas of Donggala.
Nickel mining is an important sector of the economy, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the other side of Celebes.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Response Agency, Palu and Donggala have been hit several times by tsunamis in the last 100 years.
A tsunami in 1938 killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
In 1996, West Donggala was hit by a tsunami, and nine people died.
Indonesia is located in the geologically active Pacific Ring of Fire, so earthquakes are common.
Here are just a few of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On 26 December, a huge sea quake began on the west coast of the Aceh province of North Sumatra, which launched a tsunami reaching 14 countries, which claimed a total of 226,000 lives along the Indian Ocean coast, with more than half of the victims killed in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong tremors shook the west coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
On the island of Nias, near Sumatra, hundreds died.
2006: A 6.8 quake shook the southern part of Java, Indonesia's largest island, and the tsunami following it claimed almost 700 victims on the south coast.
2009: 7.6 earthquake destroyed near Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people lost their lives.
2010: A 7.5 quake shook an island in the Mentawa archipelago near Sumatra and sometimes caused a 10-metre tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and claimed about 300 lives.
2016: A near-surface quake has hit Aceh Pidie Jaya's governorship. The panic and destruction that followed has brought back memories of the terrible tsunami in 2004.
There was no escape this time, but more than 100 inhabitants died under the collapsed buildings.
2018: Lombok is a popular Indonesian island among tourists; a powerful quake here claimed 500 lives, especially in the northern part of the island.
