How can the US-China trade war be good for Beijing?
The opening line of the trade war between the US and China was almost deafening, and although the battle was not nearly over, the break between countries could, according to experts, benefit Beijing in the long run.
US President Donald Trump issued the first warnings earlier this year by imposing a tax on major Chinese export products, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation took place this week, as the new tariffs already affect $200 billion worth of products, practically taxing half of the goods going from China to the US.
In all cases, Beijing has retaliated, most recently imposing a tariff of between five and ten percent on US goods worth $60 billion.
China has vowed to strike back every time, and the world's second largest economy will certainly not back down in the near future.
If you want to get Washington to back down, that would mean you have to cave in to the demands, but a public bow to the U.S. would be too embarrassing for Xi Chin-ping, President of China.
Still, experts say that if Beijing is good at tactics, the U.S. trade war pressure could be good for China in the long run, as it reduces dependence between the two economies.
“The fact that a quick decision in either Washington or Beijing could create conditions that could plunge any of the two countries’ economies into an economic vortex is far more serious than observers have previously acknowledged,” said Abigail Grace, Asia research assistant at the New American Security think tank.
Syria 'ready' for refugees to return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for a voluntary return of refugees and calls for help in rebuilding a country that has been destroyed in war for more than seven years.
In his speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Valid Moallem claimed that the state of the country was improving.
“The current situation is more stable and secure, thanks to the results achieved in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government will continue to restructure the areas destroyed by terrorists, restoring normal conditions.
There are now all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, who had to flee between terrorism and arbitrary economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
According to the UN, more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the outbreak of the war in 2011.
Another six million people in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Moallem said the Syrian state would welcome any assistance to rebuild the country.
But he stressed that they would not accept conditional help or assistance from countries that supported the uprising.
