Red tide news: Decreased concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, spotted flowering has been reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a decrease in concentration.
The extent of the red tide is about 130 miles of coastline, from the northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
About 10 miles outside Hillsborough County, there are spots, but compared to last week, it's a relatively smaller area.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, medium concentrations were reported in Pinellas County and off the coast, low-to-high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background-to-high concentrations in Manatee County, background-to-high concentrations in Sarasota County and off the coast, background-to-moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, background-to-high concentrations in Lee County and off the coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There were still reports of respiratory irritation in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritation from Northwest Florida.
